{{Quote|It's not illegal to be a bounty hunter.|Ailyn (Habuur) Vel|<ref name="Bloodlines" />}}
'''Ailyn Vel''' was a [[near-Human]] [[Bounty hunter/Legends|bounty hunter]], the daughter of [[Boba Fett/Legends|Boba Fett]] and [[Sintas Vel]] and the granddaughter of [[Jango Fett/Legends|Jango Fett]]. When Ailyn was just a baby, her father, Boba, was forced to leave her and her mother. By the time she was sixteen, her mother disappeared, leaving her alone.

She became a very successful bounty hunter, like her father, and devoted many years to hunting her father down to avenge her mother's death. She eventually killed a [[Spar|clone]] of her grandfather [[Jango Fett/Legends|Jango Fett]], which she believed was Boba. Afterward, she assumed the role of Boba Fett himself, and kept her real identity unknown. Shortly before the [[Yuuzhan Vong War]], Vel had a daughter, [[Mirta Gev|Mirta]].

By the time of the [[Second Galactic Civil War]], Vel had become a respectable bounty hunter like her father, and took a contract from [[Thrackan Sal-Solo]] to kill his cousin, [[Han Solo/Legends|Han Solo]]. She found out that her father was alive and attempted to use her daughter to bring Fett to her and kill him once and for all, but never got the chance. Vel was arrested by [[Darth Caedus|Jacen Solo]] on a [[Galactic Alliance Guard|GAG]] raid, and was accidentally killed by Jacen during her interrogation.

==Biography==
===Early life===
{{Quote|He never saw her for fifty years. It's not like he cares about her. What sort of father doesn't see his kid for years?|Han Solo|<ref name="Bloodlines" />}}
[[File:Fett_happy_family.png|thumb|left|150px|A [[Hologram/Legends|holographic image]] of baby Ailyn with parents [[Boba Fett/Legends|Boba Fett]] and [[Sintas Vel]].]]
Ailyn was born in approximately [[15 BBY/Legends|15 BBY]], when her father was roughly eighteen years old. The place of Ailyn's birth was unknown, though it was believed that she was born on [[Concord Dawn/Legends|Concord Dawn]], where Fett may have been a [[Journeyman Protector/Legends|Journeyman Protector]] at the time. Her mother, Sintas Vel, was a [[Kiffar/Legends|Kiffar]] bounty hunter.<ref name="Revelation" /><ref name="mandohistory" />

It seemed Ailyn's father walked out on the family (in actuality, Fett was exiled from Concord Dawn) circa [[12 BBY/Legends|12 BBY]].<ref name="TLOS">{{StoryCite|story=The Last One Standing: The Tale of Boba Fett|book=Tales of the Bounty Hunters}}</ref> As a result, Ailyn grew to hate her father. She lived with her mother until she was a teenager.<ref name="mandohistory" /> Sometime between the age of five and fourteen, she and her mother then met a man named "[[Connor Freeman|Quinny]]"<ref name="BT: BFiD #2">[[Blood Ties: Boba Fett is Dead 2|''Blood Ties: Boba Fett is Dead'' 2]]</ref>. Ailyn then helped "Quinny" and her mother fight off a hit team of [[Devaronian/Legends|Devaronians]] by using a small [[Ion cannon/Legends|ion cannon]]. After successfully fighting them off, Ailyn, her mother and Quinny then decided to go to a safe house in a nearby village.<ref name="BT: BFid #3">[[Blood Ties: Boba Fett is Dead 3|''Blood Ties: Boba Fett is Dead'' 3]]</ref>

Tragedy struck Ailyn again shortly prior to her sixteenth [[Birthday/Legends|birthday]], when her mother was presumed to have been killed while in pursuit of a bounty. Sintas had taken the bounty mission for the sole purpose of getting credits to buy a special birthday gift for her daughter. Ailyn was devastated by her mother's loss.<ref name="mandohistory" />

[[File:Young_Ailyn.jpg|thumb|220px|A young Ailyn with an ion cannon.]]

The death of Ailyn's mother fueled the strong hatred she had towards her father, and her ambition in life became killing Boba, whom Ailyn blamed for her mother's death.<ref name="mandohistory" />

Tracking Fett was a difficult task for young Ailyn, so she resorted to becoming a hunt-saboteur in hope of finding Fett in her travels. Unfortunately, her efforts went unrewarded for a long time.<ref name="mandohistory" />

===Bounty hunter===
{{Quote|Tell me, Boba Fett: under that helmet, and behind your voice synthesizer, are you perhaps&hellip;a female yourself?|Nolaa Tarkona|<ref name="Diversity Alliance">''[[Young Jedi Knights: Diversity Alliance]]''</ref>}}
It was not until some years after the reported death of Fett at the [[Great Pit of Carkoon/Legends|Great Pit of Carkoon]] that Ailyn felt she could finally move on in life. It was from that point that she began her career as a bounty hunter.<ref name="mandohistory" />

Years later, Ailyn discovered that her father still lived, and so the biggest hunt of her lifetime had resumed. She eventually hunted Fett down in the [[Extrictarium Nebula/Legends|Extrictarium Nebula]]. However, on confronting her target, she found a man that was not her father, but was in fact an old clone of Jango Fett known as [[Spar]]. Ailyn killed the old [[Advanced Recon Commando/Legends|ARC trooper]] and took his Mandalorian armor with her, and so her hunt continued.<ref name="mandohistory" />

[[File:Ailyn_Boba.jpg|thumb|left|Ailyn Vel masquerading as Boba Fett.]]
Ailyn returned to hunting bounties, and on occasion would don the Mandalorian armor and act as Boba Fett, in order to receive bounties with much larger payouts. She began to believe that she was truly Fett's equal&mdash;or better.<ref name="mandohistory" />

In [[21 ABY/Legends|21 ABY]],<ref name="GaW">''[[Galaxy at War]]''</ref> Ailyn once again believed her father to be dead. She tracked "Fett" down at [[Shogun (planet)|Shogun]] and found evidence of a dead Mandalorian supercommando. She also found Fett's ''[[Slave IV]]'' and took it as her own, assuming the corpse was that of her father.<ref name="mandohistory" />

Believing this dead man to be her father, she committed to assuming Fett's identity, taking jobs from [[Bwahl]] the [[Hutt/Legends|Hutt]] and for [[Nolaa Tarkona]] of the [[Diversity Alliance]] to find shipping merchant [[Bornan Thul]]. On the way she encountered wannabe bounty hunter [[Zekk]]. She eventually found Thul, discovering that he'd been hiding-the coordinates of a plague storehouse-and then transmitting that data to Tarkona. The Diversity Alliance crumbled in battle with the [[New Republic/Legends|New Republic]].

At some point, Ailyn had a daughter, [[Mirta Gev]]. The father was [[Makin Marec]], a [[Mandalorian/Legends|Mandalorian]] warrior she had met while researching Mandalorian culture. The two raised Mirta in the midst of the devastating Yuuzhan Vong War that would rage for much of the decade. It was probably at this time, possibly through Mirta's Mandalorian father, that Ailyn learned that her father, Boba, was indeed still alive.<ref name="Revelation" />

====Second Galactic Civil War and death====
{{Quote|My fee's five hundred thousand credits each for Han Solo and his son. If you want the Solo womenfolk and the Skywalkers, too&mdash;that'll be extra. I remember the Solo kids, but I don't think they'll recognize me again&hellip;|Ailyn Vel|<ref name="Bloodlines" />}}
By the time of the [[Second Galactic Civil War]], under the alias '''Ailyn Habuur''', she accepted Thrackan Sal-Solo's bounty on the [[Solo family/Legends|Solo family]]. What she did not know, however, was that Sal-Solo was setting her up to be caught to hide the real threat posed by other hunters he had hired for the contract. Also at this time, Ailyn told her daughter Mirta to find her father, Boba, and lure him to Coruscant with the [[Heart of Fire]] pendant that he gave to her mother, Sintas, when the two first married. She intended to kill him once and for all.<ref name="Bloodlines" />

Because of Sal-Solo's deception, Ailyn was led to [[Coruscant/Legends|Coruscant]]. There she hid in a [[Corellian/Legends|Corellian]] community and was caught during the Galactic Alliance Guard's raids. Believing her to be a Corellian terrorist, Jacen Solo interrogated her. When she did not provide information, he used the Force to bludgeon her and attempted to enter her mind. However, this was too much for Ailyn to endure, and she died.<ref name="Bloodlines" />

Mirta, who had successfully found Boba on [[Taris/Legends|Taris]], had traveled with him to [[Corellia/Legends|Corellia]]. Boba, who had learned that Ailyn took the contract to kill the Solos, found Han Solo, and tried to use him as bait to reunite with his daughter. However, Han revealed that Ailyn had been captured. Later on, Thrackan Sal-Solo revealed his deception, which resulted in Mirta killing him in a fit of rage. After Han led the two to [[Leia Organa Solo/Legends|Leia Organa Solo]], she contacted Jacen to bring her to Corellia. However, she then informed Boba and Mirta of Ailyn's death.<ref name="Bloodlines" />

Jacen Solo traveled to Corellia to bring Ailyn's corpse to Boba and Mirta. Later on, after learning from a fellow Mandalorian that Jacen Solo was the cause of Ailyn's death, Boba Fett considered hunting him down. However, he was already aware of the strife going on in the Solo family, and figured that they would cause enough damage to themselves in ways worse than he ever could.<ref name="Bloodlines" />
{{Quote|Tell me something about Ailyn. Was she ever happy?''"<br />"''I don't think so.|Boba Fett and Mirta Gev, 40 ABY|<ref name="Sacrifice">''[[Legacy of the Force: Sacrifice]]''</ref>}}
Ailyn was buried with half of the Heart of Fire pendant in a modest grave in a wooded area outside [[Keldabe/Legends|Keldabe]].<ref name="Bloodlines" /> She would never learn that her mother was still alive, having been encased in [[Carbonite/Legends|carbonite]] since around the time she took the bounty for Ailyn's present.<ref name="Sacrifice" />

[[41 ABY|A year later]], in a Coruscant [[Holozine]], Ailyn was referenced as "Fett Junior."<ref name="Revelation" />

==Behind the scenes==
{{Quote|Sweet Sith, I think I'm in love with my own creation.|Abel G. Peña|<ref name="Daughter">{{Blog|abelgpena|13|Ailyn Vel, Daughter of Boba Fett}}</ref>}}
[[File:Anastasia1.jpg|thumb|200px|Ailyn's appearance was based on that of model [[Anastasia Heonis]].]]
Ailyn Vel's character was developed by [[Abel G. Peña]], fleshed out exclusively for his article in [[Star Wars Insider 80|''Star Wars Insider'' 80]] entitled [[The History of the Mandalorians: Exploring the Evolution of a Mighty Race of Warriors|''The History of the Mandalorians'']].<ref name="Insider 80">[[Star Wars Insider 80|''Star Wars Insider'' 80]]</ref> Ailyn was designed as the typical "gorgeous butt-kicker", based on characters such as [[Wikipedia:Joan of Arc|Joan of Arc]], TV's [[Wikipedia:Xena the Warrior Princess|Xena the Warrior Princess]], [[Wikipedia:Kill Bill|''Kill Bill''<nowiki />'s]] [[Wikipedia:Beatrix Kiddo|Beatrix Kiddo]], and the prostitutes of [[Wikipedia:Frank Miller|Frank Miller's]] [[Wikipedia:Sin City|''Sin City'']].<ref name="Daughter" />

The artwork depicting Ailyn that appeared in the article was by [[Joe Corroney]], inspired by a photograph of model [[Anastasia Heonis]]. The photo was taken by Jason Perlman.<ref name="Facebook 3">{{Facebook|username=theAcidPopTart|url=photos/317840561530|name=Acid PopTart|date=February 19, 2010|quote=I was beyond geeked to be used as the model, by the talented Joe Corroney, for the newly created character, Ailyn Vel from the Star Wars Universe. Little secret: Joe and I go way back with many great talks, one being my belief that Boba Fett (my second fav character) was actually a female, a spurn lover, after Han Solo. Ailyn Vel is in fact, Boba Fett's daughter, and she's after her father with a serious vengeance now. When I got the low down on the character, I was so squeeing with delight. THANKS JOE!!! Based off a photo taken by Jason Perlman. (Appeared in Star Wars Insider Magazine)|archivedate=20211125182903}}</ref>

Ailyn assuming her father's identity was based on the concept of [[Wikipedia:Dread Pirate Roberts|Dread Pirate Roberts]] from [[Wikipedia:The Princess Bride|''The Princess Bride'']].<ref name="Daughter" />

Several reasons exist behind Peña's decision to make the appearance of Boba Fett in the second story arc of the [[Star Wars: Young Jedi Knights|''Young Jedi Knights'']] series Ailyn, instead of Fett himself. "[[The Last One Standing: The Tale of Boba Fett]]" short story, which takes place five years earlier, builds toward the suggestion that Fett's ardent animosity toward Han Solo comes to an end. His adherence to the [[Bounty Hunters' Creed]] in ''Young Jedi Knights'' also conflicts with his past behavior, having betrayed other hunters on multiple occasions, even going so far as to help destroy the [[Bounty Hunters' Guild/Legends|Bounty Hunters' Guild]] itself. The clincher for Peña was a quote given in ''[[Young Jedi Knights: Diversity Alliance]]'', in which a character speculates that Fett could be female under his helmet, to which "Fett" responds that he removes his helmet for no one.<ref name="Blog-abelgpena|15">{{Blog|abelgpena|15|The Anatomy of a Retcon 2: or, "Boba Fett? Where?"}}</ref>

Ailyn first appeared as a baby in the arms of Sintas with Boba Fett in "[[Outbid But Never Outgunned]]," though her name and character was likely not established at that time. While this story, like all other stories in the early ''[[Star Wars Tales]]'' issues, was not meant to be necessarily [[canon]], the references in ''The History of the Mandalorians'' and ''[[Legacy of the Force: Sacrifice]]'' have made her existence canonical.

